revision.text:
{{Infobox political party |country = Egypt | name = Anti-Coup Alliance |native_name = |logo = |leader = Ehab Sheiha<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com//news/pro-morsy-alliance-denies-backing-any-presidential-candidate|title=Pro-Morsy alliance denies backing any presidential candidate|publisher=Egypt Independent|date=10 February 2014|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> |colorcode = |foundation = 27 June 2013<ref name=ao28June>{{Citation|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75145/Egypt/Politics-/-Islamist-parties-launch-Legitimacy-Support-allian.aspx|title=11 Islamist parties launch 'Legitimacy Support' alliance|publisher=Ahram Online|date=28 June 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> |ideology = [[Islamism]]<ref name=ao28June/> |website = }}
The '''Anti-Coup Alliance'''<ref name=dne18Aug>{{Citation|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/08/18/anti-coup-alliance-plans-eight-marches-on-sunday/|title=Anti-Coup Alliance plans eight marches on Sunday|publisher=Daily News Egypt|date=18 August 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> (also known as the '''National Alliance Supporting Legitimacy''')<ref name=ei3Dec>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/nasl-sources-say-will-not-take-part-constitution-referendum|title=NASL sources say will not take part in constitution referendum|publisher=Egypt Independent|date=3 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> is a coalition in Egypt formed to defeat the [[2013 Egyptian coup d'état|ouster]] of former president [[Mohamed Morsi]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.ikhwanweb.com/article.php?id=31236|title=Anti-Coup Alliance Statement: Major Massacre During Crackdown Against Rabaa and Nahda Sit-Ins|publisher=Ikhwan Web|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The coalition is made up of approximately 40 Islamist parties and groups.<ref name=ao29June>{{Citation|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75211/Egypt/Politics-/Egypt-Islamist-coalition-urges-opposition-to-break.aspx|title=Egypt Islamist coalition urges opposition to break from Mubarak regime figures|publisher=Ahram Online|date=29 June 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>
==History== The coalition has called upon the opposition to break ties with figures they call "corrupt" from the [[Hosni Mubarak|Mubarak]] regime.<ref name=ao29June/> Notably, the political wing of the group (the [[Building and Development Party]]) and the [[Wasat Party]] did not take part in protests held by pro-Morsi forces during the week of 18 October 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Towards Negotiations|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/4458/17/Towards-negotiations.aspx|agency=Al-Ahram Weekly On-line|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The alliance offered a new reconciliation initiative that does not include the reinstatement of Morsi on 26 October 2013; [[al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]], [[Egyptian Islamic Jihad]] and the [[Homeland Party (Egypt)|Homeland Party]] are not calling for the reinstatement of Morsi, while the [[Virtue Party (Egypt)|Virtue Party]], [[Authenticity Party]] and the [[Muslim Brotherhood in Egypt|Muslim Brotherhood]] are still demanding that Morsi be reinstated as president.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/pro-morsy-alliance-offers-new-initiative-political-deadlock|title=Pro-Morsy alliance offers new initiative for political deadlock|publisher=Egypt Independent|date=26 October 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The group has reached out to what it called "fellow revolutionaries" to cooperate with them against the protest law in Egypt in order to jointly organize protests; [[Kefaya]] objected to the call for cooperation.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.madamasr.com/content/anti-coup-alliance-holds-out-hand-revolutionaries|title=Anti-coup alliance holds out hand to revolutionaries|publisher=Mada Masr|date=28 November 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>
Members of the [[Building and Development Party]], the political arm of [[al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]], wanted to meet with [[Yasser Al Borhamy]], the deputy head of the [[Salafist Call]] as well as [[Emad Abdel Ghaffour]], who is the head of the Homeland Party.<ref name=ei26Nov>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/pro-morsy-alliance-ask-salafis-mediate-army-end-crisis|title=Pro-Morsy alliance ask Salafis to mediate with the Army to end crisis|publisher=Egypt Independent|date=26 November 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> Al Borhamy reportedly could not meet with the members, while Ghaffour asked them to stop demonstrations before talks could begin and rebuffed their demands for the reinstatement of Morsi and the bringing back of the [[Shura Council]] that was dissolved.<ref name=ei26Nov/> Borhami denied being asked to serve as a mediator, though he stated that he would act as a mediator if there were no preconditions.<ref name=ei26Nov/> The alliance has said it will boycott the [[Egyptian constitutional referendum, 2014|2014 constitutional referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Egypt's pro-Morsi coalition to boycott constitutional referendum|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/89799.aspx|agency=Ahram Online|date=22 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>
Various groups and parties within the alliance including [[al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]], the Building and Development Party, the Islamic Party, the Freedom and Justice Party and the Virtue Party have criticized the [[Nour Party]] for its support of the draft constitution.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nour Party under Islamists’ fire over ‘yes’ vote call|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/nour-party-under-islamists-fire-over-%E2%80%98yes-vote-call|agency=Egypt Independent|date=6 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The [[Islamic Party (Egypt)|Islamic Party]] has not participated in meetings with the group because of what [[Mohamed Abu Samra]] (the secretary-general of the party) called the "[[Muslim Brotherhood of Egypt|brotherhood's]] radical thought".<ref name=cp30april>{{Cite news|url=http://thecairopost.com/news/108571/news/salafist-front-calls-on-nasl-to-suspend-activities|title=Salafist Front calls on NASL to suspend activities|work=Cairo Post|date=30 April 2014|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The [[Salafist Front]] issued a statement on 30 April 2014 that called on the alliance to temporarily stop its actions in order to avoid more violence;<ref name=cp30april/> the alliance did not suspend its activities in response.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecairopost.com/news/108746/news/108746|title=NASL hasn’t suspended activities: Watan Party|work=Cairo Post|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> Egyptian Prime minister [[Ibrahim Mahlab]] issued a decree on 16 October 2014 banning the alliance.<ref name=ao16Oct>{{Citation|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/113258.aspx|title=Egypt's PM bans pro-Morsi NASL alliance|publisher=Ahram Online|date=16 October 2014|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> Another decree was issued on 30 October 2014 which dissolved the alliance.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/30/us-egypt-brotherhood-ban-idUSKBN0IJ0QT20141030|title=Egypt bans pro-Mursi pressure group|publisher=Reuters|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> A court postponed the appeal of the dissolution of the alliance until 13 November 2014.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=06112014&id=0a6d77cd-bea5-4899-98d8-4dfea70b4629|title= تأجيل استشكال حظر "تحالف دعم الشرعية وحزب الاستقلال" لـ13 نوفمبر|publisher=Al Shorouk|date=6 November 2014|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>
==Affiliated groups== Parties and organizations in the coalition include: {{columns-list|colwidth=18em| *[[Authenticity Party]] *[[Building and Development Party]] *Civilized Alternative Party<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecairopost.com/news/86127/politics/islamist-alliance-discusses-initiative-to-end-internal-crisis|title=Islamist alliance discusses initiative to end internal crisis|work=Cairo Post|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> *[[Egyptian Islamic Labour Party]]<ref name=ei6jan>{{Cite news|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com//news/brotherhood-led-alliance-plans-referendum-day-sit-ins|title=Brotherhood-led alliance plans referendum day sit-ins|work=Egypt Independent|date=6 January 2014|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> *[[Egyptian Reform Party]] *[[Flag Party]]<ref name=mm25dec>{{cite web|url=http://madamasr.com/content/anti-coup-alliance-denies-giving-return-morsi|title=Anti-coup alliance denies giving up on the return of Morsi|work=Mada Masr|date=25 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421132830/http://www.madamasr.com/content/anti-coup-alliance-denies-giving-return-morsi|archivedate=21 April 2014}}</ref> *[[Freedom and Justice Party (Egypt)|Freedom and Justice Party]] *[[al-Jama'a al-Islamiyya|Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/jama-al-islamiya-says-nour-party-constitution-worse-church|title=Jama’a al-Islamiya says Nour Party on constitution worse than that of church|work=Egypt Independent|date=9 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> *[[New Labour Party (Egypt)|New Labor Party]]<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/28/islamist-forces-join-together-for-rabaa-al-adaweya-protest/|title=Islamist forces join together for Rabaa Al-Adaweya protest|work=Daily News Egypt|date=28 June 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> *[[People Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/12/22/anti-coup-alliance-cites-reasons-for-boycotting-referendum/|title=Anti-Coup Alliance cites reasons for boycotting referendum|work=Daily News Egypt|date=22 December 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> *[[Virtue Party (Egypt)|Virtue Party]]<ref name=ei6jan/>}}
==Withdrawals== The [[Al-Wasat Party|Wasat Party]] withdrew from the alliance on 28 August 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecairopost.com/news/123570/inside_egypt/wasat-party-withdraws-from-nasl-considers-parliamentary-elections-source|title=Wasat Party withdraws from NASL, considers parliamentary elections: Source|agency=Cairo Post|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> The [[Homeland Party (Egypt)|Homeland Party]] withdrew from the alliance on 17 September 2014, though the reason for its leaving was to reorganize itself.<ref name=ei17sept>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com//news/watan-party-withdraws-nasl|title=Watan Party withdraws from NASL|publisher=Egypt Independent|date=17 September 2014|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> The [[Authenticity Party]] is considering leaving the alliance because it has not achieved its goals.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/537901|title=تحالف "المعزول" يحتضر|publisher=Al Masry Al Youm|date=4 October 2014|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> The [[Salafist Front]] had withdrawn from the alliance on 30 November 2014.<ref name=dne6dec>{{cite news|title=More Islamist groups withdraw from Anti-Coup Alliance|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2014/12/06/islamist-groups-withdraw-anti-coup-alliance/|work=Daily News Egypt|date=6 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> The [[Independence Party (Egypt)|Independence Party]] announced on 4 December 2014 that it had withdrawn.<ref name=dne6dec/> The [[Arab Unification Party]] and the [[Islamic Party (Egypt)|Islamic Party]] have withdrawn from the Anti-Coup Alliance.<ref name=amay5dec>{{cite news|title=نهاية تحالف "دعم المعزول"|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/593739|work=Al Masry Al Youm|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> [[al-Jama'a al-Islamiyya|al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]] is considering withdrawing from the alliance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamaa Islamiya urges pro-Morsi coalition to run for parliament|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/jamaa-islamiya-urges-pro-morsi-coalition-run-parliament|work=Egypt Independent|date=10 August 2015|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> Osama Hafez, the leader of the groups shura council, has called on the organization to withdraw from the alliance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Osama Hafez succeeds Essam Derbala as Jama'a al-Islamiya Shura Council president|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/osama-hafez-succeeds-essam-derbala-jama-al-islamiya-shura-council-president|work=Egypt Independent|date=11 August 2015|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>
==Court cases== A court verdict that could have banned the alliance was not given on 21 May 2014 because the Cairo Court for Urgent Matters ruled that it lacked jurisdiction.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com//news/court-decrees-lack-jurisdiction-lawsuit-demanding-nasl-ban|title=Court decrees lack of jurisdiction in lawsuit demanding NASL ban |publisher=Egypt Independent|date=21 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> An appeal to dissolve the coalition was thrown out on 22 September 2014 partly because it did not indicate what parties are part of the alliance and did not indicate the coalitions alleged connections to "terrorist activities".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.madamasr.com/content/cairo-court-dismisses-lawsuits-against-nour-party-mb-affiliated-alliance|title=Cairo court dismisses lawsuits against Nour Party, MB-affiliated alliance|date=22 September 2014|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Mada Masr}}</ref> Another verdict in September 2014 banned the alliance.<ref name=ao16Oct/>
