{{Intersex sidebar}}
[[Intersex]] people in [[Uganda]] face a dangerous environment, with significant gaps in protection from mutilation and non-consensual cosmetic medical interventions and protection from discrimination.

==History==
{{further|Intersex in history}}
Traditionally, children who are identified as having an intersex condition at birth were killed, and mothers may be accused of witchcraft.<ref name="sipd2016" /> This is beginning to change, with the help of intersex civil society organizations like SIPD Uganda, but stigma, violence, abuse and exploitation still persist.<ref name="sipd2016">{{Cite| last = Support Initiative for Persons with Congenital Disorders| title = Baseline Survey on Intersex Realities in East Africa - Specific Focus on Uganda, Kenya and Rwanda| date = 2016}}</ref><ref name="kaggwa2016id">{{Cite web| last = Kaggwa| first = Julius| author-link = Julius Kaggwa| title = Understanding intersex stigma in Uganda| work = [[Intersex Day]]| accessdate = 2017-05-13| date = October 2016| url = http://intersexday.org/en/understanding-stigma-uganda/| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170408064123/http://intersexday.org/en/understanding-stigma-uganda/| archivedate = 2017-04-08| df = }}</ref>

In December 2017, African intersex activists published a statement setting out local demands.<ref>{{Cite| last = African Intersex Movement| title = Public Statement by the African Intersex Movement| date = December 2017| url = https://www.astraeafoundation.org/stories/public-statement-african-intersex-movement/ | accessdate = 2018-09-05}}</ref>

== Physical integrity and bodily autonomy ==
[[File:Protection of intersex children from harmful practices.svg|thumb|right|260px|
{{legend|#002255|Legal prohibition of non-consensual [[Intersex medical interventions|medical interventions]]}}
{{legend|#0066FF|Regulatory suspension of non-consensual medical interventions}}]]
{{further|Intersex human rights|Intersex medical interventions}}
Reports suggest that the birth of an intersex infant can be regarded as a curse or bad omen, resulting in infanticide, neglect, and the stigmatization of the mother.<ref name="kaggwa2016id" /> Mothers may even be expelled from their community, and intersex children may be separated from siblings.<ref name="sipd2016" /><ref name="cschrcl" />

Intersex persons may experience coercive medical interventions, in medical settings and outside medical settings. However, intersex persons who require medical attention may also have difficulties accessing necessary treatment.<ref name="sipd2016" /><ref name="Scope2014">{{Cite web| last = Richter| first = Ruthann| title = In Uganda, offering support for those born with indeterminate sex| work = [[Stanford Medicine]]| date = March 4, 2014| url = http://scopeblog.stanford.edu/2014/03/04/in-uganda-offering-support-for-those-born-with-indeterminate-sex/| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150730131438/http://scopeblog.stanford.edu/2014/03/04/in-uganda-offering-support-for-those-born-with-indeterminate-sex/| archivedate = July 30, 2015| df = }}</ref>

A 2014 Civil Society Coalition on Human Rights and Constitutional Law report identified multiple cases where surgeries and medical interventions led to human rights abuses. In one case, surgery conducted by medical practitioners without family consent led to the child having health problems and dropping out of school.<ref name="cschrcl">{{Cite web| last1 = Civil Society Coalition on Human Rights and Constitutional Law| last2 = Human Rights Awareness and Promotion Forum| last3 = Rainbow Health Foundation| last4 = Sexual Minorities Uganda| last5 = Support Initiative for Persons with Congenital Disorders| author4-link = Sexual Minorities Uganda| title = Uganda Report of Violations based on Sex Determination, Gender Identity, and Sexual Orientation| date = 2014| url = http://www.hrapf.org/publications/research-papers/uganda-report-violations-based-sex-determination-gender-identity-and| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150503012642/http://www.hrapf.org/publications/research-papers/uganda-report-violations-based-sex-determination-gender-identity-and| archivedate = 2015-05-03| df = }}</ref> In another case, a child was abandoned at hospital after genital surgery because of the cost of treatment. The hospital discontinued his treatment.<ref name="cschrcl" />

Sam Lyomoki, a Ugandan MP and a doctor, has stated that the parliament "issued guidelines in 2015 to the Ministry of Health advising against surgical intervention for intersex infants", however, "Local radio stations in Uganda buzz with appeals seeking donors to help fund genital reshaping surgery abroad" and surgeries are also carried out within Uganda.<ref name="kakande2016" /> Local organization SIPD Uganda "advocates for the 'best guess' non-surgical approach where an intersex child should be raised in the best-suited gender, without irreversible surgical intervention, until they can be active participants in the decision".<ref name="kakande2016">{{cite web | url = http://news.trust.org/item/20161218060443-tqfr4/ | title = In Uganda, parents seek controversial genital surgery for 'intersex' babies | first = Yasin | last = Kakande | work = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] News | date = December 18, 2016 | accessdate = 2017-05-15 | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161221004250/http://news.trust.org/item/20161218060443-tqfr4 | archivedate = December 21, 2016 | df =  }}</ref>

==Protection from discrimination==
[[File:Inclusion of sex characteristics in anti-discrimination law.svg|thumb|right|260px|
{{legend|#002255|Explicit protection from [[Discrimination against intersex people|discrimination]] on grounds of [[sex characteristics]]}}
{{legend|#0066FF|Explicit protection on grounds of intersex status}}
{{legend|#9FCFFF|Explicit protection on grounds of intersex within attribute of sex}}]]
{{main|Discrimination against intersex people}}
The constitution of Uganda provides for recognition of fundamental rights and freedoms, equality and non-discrimination, privacy, education and affirmative action.<ref name="sipd2016" /> The African Charter on the rights and welfare of the African child commits member countries, including Uganda, to the protection of all children – including intersex children – against social, economic, cultural and political abuse and exploitation.<ref name="sipd2016" /> In practice, intersex persons remain subject to violence, discrimination and abuse.<ref name="kaggwa2016gu">{{Cite news| issn = 0261-3077| last = Kaggwa| first = Julius| title = I'm an intersex Ugandan – life has never felt more dangerous| work = [[The Guardian]]| accessdate = 2017-05-13| date = September 16, 2016| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/16/intersex-ugandan-lgbt-gay-rights-life-never-felt-more-dangerous| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170309004148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/16/intersex-ugandan-lgbt-gay-rights-life-never-felt-more-dangerous| archivedate = March 9, 2017| df = }}</ref>

In research by SIPD Uganda, 90% of intersex youth reported that they were forced to drop out of school because of the immense stigma and discrimination associated with the non-binary development of their intersex body."<ref name="sipd2016" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ippf.org/stories/growing-intersex-uganda | title = Growing up intersex in Uganda | work = [[International Planned Parenthood Federation]] | accessdate = 2017-05-15 | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170614122846/http://www.ippf.org/stories/growing-intersex-uganda | archivedate = 2017-06-14 | df =  }}</ref>

==Identification documents==
{{main|Legal recognition of intersex people}}
The Registration of Persons Act 2015 allows for the registration of a child born a "hermaphrodite", and for change of name and change of sex classification. The recommendation of a medical clinician is required. Changes of name can create social problems, and the situation of adults is uncertain.<ref name="reg2015">{{Cite| last = Parliament of Uganda| title = Registration of Persons Act| date = 2015| url = http://www.ulii.org/ug/legislation/act/2015/4-6| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170501145417/http://www.ulii.org/ug/legislation/act/2015/4-6| archivedate = 2017-05-01| df = }}</ref><ref name="sipd2016" /> Many intersex persons are understood to be stateless due to historical difficulties in obtaining identification documents.<ref name="sipd2016" />

== Rights advocacy==
SIPD Uganda has called for recognition of the human rights of intersex people in Uganda, and in the East African region, including protection from harmful surgeries, access to care, protection from discrimination and abuse, and access to education and employment. SIPD Uganda has worked with some 700 intersex persons in the 25 Ugandan administrative districts where it delivers services.<ref name="Scope2014" /> The organization also convened a 2014 regional meeting of intersex advocates allies from Rwanda, Burundi, Kenya, Congo, Tanzania, and Uganda.<ref name="sipd2016" />

Intersex is commonly confused with being lesbian or gay, and this has consequences for organizing and disclosure, as well as discrimination towards intersex persons. [[Julius Kaggwa]], the executive director of SIPD, describes the situation in Uganda as dangerous.<ref name="kaggwa2016gu" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/julius-kaggwa/uganda-lgbti-rights_b_1821740.html |title=Life's No Play, But Certain Characters' Voices Are Heard Loud and Clear in Uganda |last1=Kaggwa |first1=Julius |date=August 24, 2012 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=The World Post |access-date=2015-07-20 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233819/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/julius-kaggwa/uganda-lgbti-rights_b_1821740.html |archivedate=September 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/julius-kaggwa/ugandan-anti-homosexualit_b_463810.html |title=Ugandan Anti-Homosexuality Bill Doubly Endangers LGBT Community and Human Rights Activists |last1=Kaggwa |first1=Julius |date=April 18, 2010 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=The World Post |access-date=2015-07-20 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233821/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/julius-kaggwa/ugandan-anti-homosexualit_b_463810.html |archivedate=September 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39053828 | title = Becoming Julius: Growing up intersex in Uganda | date = February 26, 2017 | work = [[BBC News]] | accessdate = 2017-05-15 | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170524225801/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39053828 | archivedate = May 24, 2017 | df =  }}</ref>

