[[Image:Archbishop_Matthew_Parker.jpg|thumb|Archbishop [[Matthew Parker]]]]{{Portal|Anglicanism}}
The '''Nag's Head Fable''' was a fiction which purported that [[Matthew Parker]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] under [[Elizabeth I]], was consecrated with a Bible pressed to his neck in the Nag's Head tavern in [[Cheapside]]. The story surfaced more than 40 years after Parker's consecration and was spread by some [[Roman Catholic]]s as fact until the dawn of the 20th century. __NOTOC__ ==Fact and fiction== On the passing of the [[Act of Uniformity 1559]], shortly after the start of [[Elizabeth I]]'s reign, fourteen [[bishops]] were dismissed from their [[diocese|sees]], and all the other sees, except [[Diocese of Llandaff|Llandaff]] (then part of the [[Church of England]]), were at the time vacant.{{sfn|Brewer|1894}} [[Matthew Parker]] had been selected as Archbishop of Canterbury, but there was a question of how to obtain [[consecration]] so as to preserve unbroken [[apostolic succession]], as the [[Bishop of Llandaff]], [[Anthony Kitchin]], opposed Parker's appointment and refused to officiate.{{sfn|Brewer|1894}} The allegation of an indecent consecration in the Nag's Head Fable seems first to have been made by a [[Jesuit]], [[Christopher Holywood]], in 1604, over 40 years after the event.
According to [[propaganda]], [[John Scory]], the deposed [[Bishop of Chichester]], was sent for and officiated at the Nag's Head tavern in [[Cheapside]].{{sfn|Brewer|1894}} There Parker was supposedly consecrated by having a Bible pressed to his neck while Scory said, "Take thou authority to preach the word of God sincerely."{{sfn|Brewer|1894}}
This story was later discredited, as a full eyewitness description was found of the consecration of Parker, in [[Lambeth Palace Chapel]], by bishops Scory, [[William Barlow (bishop of Chichester)|William Barlow]], [[Myles Coverdale]], and [[John Hodgkins]]. In this account it is stated that it was not the consecration which took place at the Nag's Head, but only that those who took part in it dined there subsequently.{{sfn|Moss|1965|loc=ch.&nbsp;64}}
As recently as the late nineteenth century, the legend was still being told as fact by controversialists in such countries as [[Sri Lanka]].{{sfn|Moss|1965|loc=ch.&nbsp;64}}
